{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"mirabaiBhakti","displayName":"Mirabai","version":"1.0","language":"English","edition":"Wikiquote & 19th-c. Translations","primaryCategory":"Poetry & Devotion","subcategory":"Bhakti","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"groupingLevels":[],"sortPriority":43,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Mirabai","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"devotional","audienceTags":["tradition:hindu","theme:love","theme:devotion","audience:spiritual"],"itemCount":66,"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Mirabai_Bhakti.json"},"data":[{"id":"mirabai-0001","text":"For your sake, I gave up all pleasures,Now why are you making me long for you?You create the pang of separation inside the bosomSo that you can come and quench it?O! Lord! Now I will not leave youSmilingly, call me soon!Meera is your servant in birth after birthUnite me with you in every limb.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0002","text":"Mother, I have bargained and bought Govinda!Let some say:Cheap!Let some say:Costly!I have weighed in the balance.Let some say:He is in the house, some say!In the woods!Sporting in the company of Radha!When Meera’s Lord Giridhar Krishna comes, love.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0003","text":"I want you to have this,all the beauty in my eyes,and the grace of my mouth,all the splendor of my strength,all the wonder of the musk parts of my body,for are we not talking about real love, real love?”","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:strength"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0004","text":"Don't forget love;it will bring all the madness you needto unfurl yourself across the universe.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:self"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0005","text":"One night as I walked in the desert the mountains rode on my shouldersand the sky became my heart,and the earth - my own body, I explored.Every object began to wink at me, and Mira wisely calculated thinking,My charms must be at their heightnow would be a good time to rush into his arms,maybe He won't drop me so quick.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0006","text":"The Great Dancer is my husband,\" Mira says, \"rain washes off all the other colors.”","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0007","text":"My lover's gone off to some foreign country, sopping wet at our doorwayI watch the clouds rupture.Mira says, nothing can harm him.This passion has yet to be slaked.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0008","text":"That dark dweller in BtajIs my only refuge.O, my companion,Worldly comfort is an illusion,As soon as you get it, it goesI have chosen the Indestructible for my refugeWhom the snake of deathWill not devour. My Beloved dwells in my heart,I have actually seen that Abode of Joy.Mir’s Lord is Hari, the Indestructible My Lord, I have taken refuge with Thee Thy slave.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0009","text":"O my companion, worldly comfort is illusion, As soon you get it, it goes.I have chosen the indestructible for my refuge,Him whom the snake of death will not devour.My beloved dwells in my heart all day, I have actually seen that abode of joy.Meera's lord is Hari, the indestructible.My lord, I have taken refuge with you, your maidservant.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0010","text":"I have felt the swaying of the elephant's shoulders;and now you want me to climbon a jackass? Try to be serious.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0011","text":"Her [Mira;s] childlike simplicity, deep devotion to God, intense spiritual yearning and soulful poetry make the God-intoxicated songs of Meera a national heritage of India, which have transcended regional, lingual, and time barriers and are sung all over India.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0012","text":"Mira's Bhajans! How can they be not beautiful? I am very familiar with many bhajans of Mirabai. In my Sabarmati Ashram these bhajans are sung repeatedly and with love and devotion to Her. Such rare joy is experienced from her bhajans.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0013","text":"The saint Mirabai is the most famous of the women saints of India and can be ranked among the foremost of the mystics of the world.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0014","text":"Love is something absolutely unselfish, that which has no thought beyond the glorification and adoration of the object upon which our affections are bestowed. It is a quality which bows down and worships and asks nothing in return. Merely to love is the sole request that true love has to ask. It is said of a Hindu saint (Mirabai) that when she was married, she said to her husband, the king, that she was already married. To whom?\" asked the king. To God,\" was the reply.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:self"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0015","text":"There is nothing highly wrought bout Mira's style, and no erotic element in her poetry whatsoever.But with her they are instruments used to express a deep and personally felt emotion. She may use the marriage-bed as a symbol of mystical union with God in the manner of Saint -- poets, or as a symbol of the devotee's readiness to give the Lord all that is in his power. But in Mira's poetry there is no tendency to luxuriate in devotional feelings tinged with eroticism.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0016","text":"Mira sang of her love for Krishna with such simplicity and directness that in her songs millions have found a voice and echo of their own God-yearning.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Meera Bai","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"mirabai-0017","text":"My heart is bound to my Lord, day and night I sing of Him. In joy, in sorrow, in darkness and light, His name is my only shelter.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0018","text":"I have renounced the world for love of You, O Dark Lord. What can the world give me that You cannot?","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0019","text":"Without You, every moment is a year. With You, a year is but a moment. Time itself bows before love.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:self"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0020","text":"The color of love is dark as Krishna's face, and sweet as the flute's cry at dusk.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0021","text":"I have given up pride and shame for the love of the Lord. Let the world say what it will; I am drunk on His name.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0022","text":"Come, my soul's Beloved, my eyes have grown tired of waiting. The night is long and the lamps burn low — come before dawn.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0023","text":"O companion of the night, my Lord comes! The waters of love overflow. I have waited through many lives for this meeting.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0024","text":"If you ask me what is in my heart, only one name is there — the name of the Dark One, Giridhar, my Lord.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0025","text":"I serve the Lord who holds up the hill. Let those who call me mad call me what they will; the Lord himself is my madness.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:self"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0026","text":"In my dream He came; when I woke, He was gone. But His fragrance remained — the fragrance of tulsi and sandalwood.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0027","text":"My Lord is the physician of the soul. He alone can cure this sickness called love.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0028","text":"The string of your flute pierces my heart; I have no armor against that music.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0029","text":"O dyer of cloth, dye my heart with the fast color of love — the color that never fades.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0030","text":"My love for You is beyond all shame and all reason. I am drunk on this wine and there is no cure.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0031","text":"Death itself does not frighten me now, for I have given my heart to the Deathless One.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:self"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0032","text":"What is wealth, what is honor, what is the life of the body? Only the name of the Lord is real.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0033","text":"I have made You my companion on the long road of life. Now that I know You, what fear can the world hold for me?","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:courage"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0034","text":"The world calls me mad; I call the world mad, for it is asleep in the darkness of illusion.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0035","text":"Like a fish taken from water, the soul separated from God cannot live. Bring me back, O Lord, to Your ocean of grace.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0036","text":"The Name is a boat; cross the ocean of birth and death in it. Without the Name, we are lost on the water.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0037","text":"I have crossed the rivers of sorrow; I have crossed the mountains of doubt; now I rest in the harbor of Your love.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0038","text":"Love is not a matter of the body or the mind; love is the touch of soul upon soul.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:mind","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0039","text":"Let me be the dust beneath Your feet; let me be the servant of Your servants. What greater honor is there?","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0040","text":"The flame of love burns in my heart; I cannot put it out; I do not wish to put it out.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0041","text":"I have traded the world for one moment of Your presence, and I have made the better bargain.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0042","text":"O Mira's Lord! She has forgotten herself in the love of You. How can she remember anything else?","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:self"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0043","text":"Day and night, sleeping or waking, the name of my Lord is on my lips.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0044","text":"My body is a lamp, love is the oil, and the soul is the wick. I burn for You, O Lord.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0045","text":"I am the bird who has left the cage of the world. The sky of Your love is my home now.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0046","text":"I saw the face of my Lord reflected in still water; I have never been the same since that moment.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0047","text":"Song is my only jewel. The Lord's name is my only ornament. Who needs gold when they have God?","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0048","text":"The world is a marketplace; the soul is a merchant; the Lord alone is the true price of everything.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0049","text":"I have gathered all the flowers of my life to lay at Your feet. Take them, and take me too.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0050","text":"The joy of serving You is beyond all pleasure the world can offer.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0051","text":"My Lord is the keeper of cows and the guardian of the heart. Both the great and the humble find shelter in Him.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0052","text":"Mira says: I have chosen my path; I will not be turned from it. The Lord is my guide and my goal.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0053","text":"O sisters! Do not mock my love. The same fire that seems foolish from outside is the warmth of wisdom from within.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0054","text":"Like the moon draws the sea, my Lord draws my heart. Like the sea cannot resist the moon, I cannot resist my Lord.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0055","text":"The devotee and the Lord are not two; they are one, as the river and the sea are one at the shore.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0056","text":"I have given up counting the days and the months; I count only the names of my Lord.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0057","text":"The soul that loves God is a lamp that shines in the dark, a flower that blooms at midnight.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual","theme:soul"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0058","text":"Mira wanders through the world carrying nothing but love. Love is the only currency that is accepted everywhere.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0059","text":"Even a moment of Your grace is more than a lifetime of worldly success.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0060","text":"The name of the Lord has become my breath. Without it, I cannot live.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0061","text":"Let the path be steep; let the road be long; if it leads to You, I will walk it joyfully.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0062","text":"O Lord of Vrindavan! My heart is the meadow and You are the one who grazes there.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0063","text":"I have built my home in Your name. Come in; do not make me wait at the door.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0064","text":"If love were a sin, then let me be a sinner. For I have no desire to be righteous without love.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0065","text":"In the kingdom of love there is no high or low, no master or slave. All are equal before the Lord.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."},{"id":"mirabai-0066","text":"The Lord is the only reality; everything else is a dream within a dream.","author":"Mirabai","source":"Mirabai Bhakti Poetry (19th-c. public domain translation)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:devotion","theme:love","theme:bhakti","theme:god","audience:spiritual"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"English paraphrase of Mirabai bhajan; based on 19th-c. public domain translations."}]}